I’ll do exactly whats mentioned above. First lets explore the data that we are dealing with. It is data related

learning <- read.csv("data/learning2014.csv",header = T)
str(learning)
## 'data.frame':    166 obs. of  7 variables:
##  $ gender  : chr  "F" "M" "F" "M" ...

##  $ surf    : num  2.58 3.17 2.25 2.25 2.83 ...
##  $ points  : int  25 12 24 10 22 21 21 31 24 26 ...

Here you can see some structures of the data. As demonstrated, we have 166 observation containing 7 different variables. Gender is in this case binomial containing M (Male) and F (Female). Age (in years) is derived from the date of birth. Attitude describes global attitude toward statistics and it is the mean of several observation. Variables deep, stra and surf are describing the averages from different questions. The last variable points is the number of points from the exam.

Here is some figures showing some of the important findings from this study.

library(ggplot2)

These two relationship shown above seems to be rather interesting. Surprisingly or not, if the attitude is better the learning outcome is better. Additionally, higher age correlates with lower learning outcome, especially for male. On the other hand plots below are not that interesting although they demonstrate the different between sex.

Next we are going to evaluate the relationship of the variables with linear model.

my_model <- lm(points ~ gender+age+attitude+deep+stra+surf, data = learning)

# summary of the model

After linear modeling and statistical testing, one can see that there is not so much difference. P value of the whole model is 1.599e-07, which means there is at least one variable effecting to points value.

T-test value probabilities Pr(>|t|) describe the change in dependent value after change in explanatory variable. The cut off for significance is typically alfa = 0.05. With this cutoff attitude is the only variable inducing significant changes so fitting new model with it.

my_model2 <- lm(points ~ attitude, data = learning)

# summary of the model
summary(my_model2)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = points ~ attitude, data = learning)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -16.9763  -3.2119   0.4339   4.1534  10.6645 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)  11.6372     1.8303   6.358 1.95e-09 ***
## attitude      3.5255     0.5674   6.214 4.12e-09 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 5.32 on 164 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.1906, Adjusted R-squared:  0.1856 
## F-statistic: 38.61 on 1 and 164 DF,  p-value: 4.119e-09

In this model estimates are about 11.6 and 3.52 meaning that value of dependant variable is 11.6 when explanatory variable is x = 0. Estimate of attitude tells that dependant variable increase 3.52 ‘points’ when attitude increase by 1.

Multiple R-squared is 0.19 meaning that residuals are quite big and that this model is not nessesary the best for this data. To get better look of residuals several visualization can be done.

par(mar = c(4, 4, .1, .1))
# par(mfrow = c(2,2))
plot(my_model2, which = c(1,2,5))

Assumptions related to linear model are obviously linearity and that the distribution is normally distributed. The model follows normality assumption quite good as can be seen from QQ-plot. Furthermore, there is a constant variance in errors as can be seen in residual plot and non of the points have unusually high leverage to the model. As a sum up, the model describes the relationship between points and attitude quite good.

This data is from Portuguese secondary school and it describes the alcohol consumption habits. It was collected by using questionnaires and school reports. Here we have combined data set and they represent performing in Mathematics and Portuguese language.

More information can be found from here.

Hypothesis

If I have to guess Ill take these four variables that could explain high alcohol consumption. Below there is some thoughts why. goout - going out with friends (numeric: from 1 - very low to 5 - very high) - Typically if one is going out often alcohol may play some role. studytime - weekly study time (numeric: 1 - <2 hours, 2 - 2 to 5 hours, 3 - 5 to 10 hours, or 4 - >10 hours) - If one is studing more often the alcohol consumption is lover. G3 - final grade (numeric: from 0 to 20, output target) - Final grade is often good if one havent drink so much absences - number of school absences (numeric: from 0 to 93) - Typically people that are not often seen at school are more often seen at bar.

Odds ratios tell basically how good predictors are the explanatory variables. If the value is higher than 1 variable predicts high use and if its smaller it predicts low use. In this case G3 is close to 1 and its confidence intervals are below and above 1 meaning that it is not good predictor. All the other predictor odds ratios and confidences are above (goout and absence) or below (studytime) 1. This gives the same interpretation as p-values from the statistical model.

Prediction power

library(dplyr)
## Warning: package 'dplyr' was built under R version 4.0.5
## 
## Attaching package: 'dplyr'
## The following objects are masked from 'package:stats':
## 
##     filter, lag
## The following objects are masked from 'package:base':
## 
##     intersect, setdiff, setequal, union
mod <- glm(high_use ~ goout + studytime  + absences , data = alc)

#prediction and observing the data
prob <- predict(mod, type = "response")
alc <- mutate(alc, probability = prob)
alc <- mutate(alc, prediction = probability > 0.5)
select(alc, failures, absences, studytime, high_use, probability, prediction) %>% tail(10)

According to these tests my three predictive variables are not enough to reliably predict high alcohol use. Fortunately, most of the predictions are right. The number table shows exactly the same thing as the proportion table. The model is predicting too much high alcohol users. From the tables one can read that 88/370. i.e. about 24% of the predicted variables are wrong.

Results are expected, as typically this complex data set is hard to predict. Against expectations the G3 variable (grades) was not good predictor and thus dropped out.

Cross-validation

library(boot)
toCV <- function(class, prob) {
  n_wrong <- abs(class - prob) > 0.5
  mean(n_wrong)
}

toCV(class = alc$high_use, prob = alc$probability)
## [1] 0.2378378
cv <- cv.glm(data = alc, cost = toCV, glmfit = mod, K = 10)

# average number of wrong predictions in the cross validation
cv$delta[1]
## [1] 0.2459459

The number of wrong predictions is near 0.24, so very similar to simplified model evaluation.

This boston data set is contains 506 observations in 14 following variables:

crim = per capita crime rate by town.

zn = proportion of residential land zoned for lots over 25,000 sq.ft.

indus = proportion of non-retail business acres per town.

chas = Charles River dummy variable (= 1 if tract bounds river; 0 otherwise).

nox = nitrogen oxides concentration (parts per 10 million).

rm = average number of rooms per dwelling.

age = proportion of owner-occupied units built prior to 1940.

dis = weighted mean of distances to five Boston employment centres.

rad = index of accessibility to radial highways.

tax = full-value property-tax rate per $10,000.

ptratio = pupil-teacher ratio by town.

black = 1000(Bk - 0.63)^2 where Bk is the proportion of blacks by town.

lstat = lower status of the population (percent).

medv = median value of owner-occupied homes in $1000s.

lda.arrows <- function(x, myscale = 1, arrow_heads = 0.1, color = "blue", tex = 0.75, choices = c(1,2)){
  heads <- coef(x)
  arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0, 
         x1 = myscale * heads[,choices[1]], 
         y1 = myscale * heads[,choices[2]], col=color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads), 
       cex = tex, col=color, pos=3)
}

classes <- as.numeric(training$crim)

plot(ldamod, dimen = 2, col = classes, pch = classes)
lda.arrows(ldamod, myscale = 2)

The prediction is pretty good for high and low but not so good especially for med_low group. Of course the training set and testing set are randomly assigned meaning that the result is changing every time it goes through. More validation is needed to have better evaluation.

Plotting is not very efficient with all the variables so only plotting nox, rm, age, dis, rad and tax variables.

km <-kmeans(boston_scaled2, centers = 4)
pairs(boston_scaled2[,5:10], col = km$cluster)

Next trying to figure out best number of clusters.

set.seed(17)
k_max <- 10
twcss <- sapply(1:k_max, function(k){kmeans(boston_scaled2, k)$tot.withinss})
qplot(x = 1:k_max, y = twcss, geom = 'line') + theme_bw()

This exploration indicates that increasing number of clusters over 2 wont give dramatically better results. Therefor 2 clusters will give the best results.

km <-kmeans(Boston, centers = 2)
pairs(boston_scaled2[,6:10], col = km$cluster)

The best separation between groups can be found in variables tax (property tax-rate) and rad (distance to the radial highways).

All the variables were plotted at first but they didn’t provide any further information and only made figures harder to read so they are not shown.
